What is Seaborn?¶

Python's most well-known package for creating plots is called matplotlib. seaborn is a Python package that has a slightly friendlier syntax (more similar to that of ggplot2 in R), that calls matplotlib in the background. We'll start by importing the pandas and seaborn packages, and also importing just the pyplot module of matplotlib (so we can save our plots later on). seaborn comes with some datasets built in, so we load in the penguins dataset that contains observations taken from penguins in Antarctica.

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

penguins = sns.load_dataset('penguins')
penguins

Scatter plots¶

We can quickly generate some nice scatter plots using seaborn's relplot() function (for "relationship plot"). We give the data, x, y, and hue arguments (hue being the variable we want mapped to the colour). We automatically get the legend created for us.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702c302f20>

We can map a variable to the size of the points.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species',
    size = 'body_mass_g'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17028c6b8b0>

Or to the style (shape) of the points.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data  = penguins,
    x     = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y     = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue   = 'species',
    style = 'sex'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702c58d540>

If we want to include plots of the marginal distributions of each variable, we can use the jointplot() function, giving the same arguments as before. Play around with the space argument to see its effect.

In [ ]:
sns.jointplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = "bill_length_mm", 
    y    = "bill_depth_mm", 
    hue  = "species",
    space = 0
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x1702c515210>

We can overlay contour lines onto this plot if we like using the plot_joint() method. Experiment with the bw_adjust argument (default is 1).

In [ ]:
p1 = sns.jointplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species', 
    space = 0
)

p1.plot_joint(sns.kdeplot, bw_adjust = 1.5)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.JointGrid at 0x1702cb84ca0>

If we want a quick visualisation of all pairwise relationships, we can use the pairplot() function (careful if you have many veriables).

In [ ]:
sns.pairplot(data=penguins, hue = "species")
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x1702d266c50>

Line plots¶

When wanting to represent how a quantity changes over time, we will often employ line graphs. As our penguins dataset doesn’t lend itself to this kind of plotting, we’re going to load a new dataset with the numbers of passengers by month and year (I can't find a proper description of this dataset so can't say more than that).

In [ ]:
flights = sns.load_dataset('flights')
flights
Out[ ]:
year month passengers
0 1949 Jan 112
1 1949 Feb 118
2 1949 Mar 132
3 1949 Apr 129
4 1949 May 121
... ... ... ...
139 1960 Aug 606
140 1960 Sep 508
141 1960 Oct 461
142 1960 Nov 390
143 1960 Dec 432

144 rows × 3 columns

We can plot this data using our familiar relplot() function, but setting kind = 'line'. This draws a line between each observation, with a different line per year.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data = flights,
    x    = 'month',
    y    = 'passengers',
    hue  = 'year',
    kind = 'line'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f4e5cf0>

If we want to draw the individual points as well, we can set marker = 'o' (or another marker shape).

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data = flights,
    x    = 'month',
    y    = 'passengers',
    hue  = 'year',
    kind = 'line',
    marker = 'o'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f5b6020>

If we want a smooth polynomial through each year's data points instead, we first extract the months as integers, then use lmplot ("linear model plot"), adjusting the order of the polynomial depending on how "wiggly" we want our smooths to be. I also use ci = None to suppress confidence intervals.

In [ ]:
flights['month_int'] = pd.Categorical(flights.month).codes

sns.lmplot(
    data  = flights,
    x     = 'month_int', 
    y     = 'passengers',
    hue   = 'year',
    order = 5,
    ci    = None
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f07f2b0>

We can do something similar if we want separate regression lines drawn per group.

In [ ]:
sns.lmplot(
    data  = penguins,
    x     = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y     = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue   = 'species',
    ci    = 95,
    order = 1
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f588790>

Plotting categorical data¶

When plotting a categorical variable against a continuous one, we often make use of bar plots, boxplots, and violin plots.

Let’s start by creating a bar chart to show the frequency of each penguin species using catplot() (for "categorical plot"), by setting kind = 'count'.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(data = penguins, x = 'species', kind = 'count')
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1701a074460>

If we want to plot a categorical variable against a continuous one, we still use catplot() but provide x and y arguments, and omit the kind argument.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(data = penguins, x = 'species', y = 'bill_length_mm')
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1701a0a91b0>

By default the points are "jittered" horizontally to reduce overplotting, but we can turn this off by setting jitter = False.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(data = penguins, x = 'species', y = 'bill_length_mm', jitter = False)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f3cfd30>

We can also set kind = 'swarm' to get a swarm plot where points are jittered horizontally to avoid overlaps.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(data = penguins, x = 'species', y = 'bill_length_mm', kind = 'swarm')
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702f3ce260>

We can still map variables to the hue argument.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = 'species', 
    y    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    hue  = 'sex',
    kind = 'swarm'
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1701a49d690>

There's no rule that says the categorical variable must be on the x axis. Sometimes, it's even better to have it mapped to the y axis. If we want the categorical variable to appear in a specific order, we simply give a list of the categories in our desired order to the order argument.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'species', 
    hue  = 'sex',
    kind = 'swarm',
    order = ['Adelie', 'Gentoo', 'Chinstrap']
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17030fbed40>

We can create a boxplot by setting kind = 'box', and the boxes are automatically "dodged" side-by-side for us.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'species', 
    hue  = 'sex',
    kind = 'box',
    order = ['Adelie', 'Gentoo', 'Chinstrap']
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1702fdebbe0>

Similar to a boxplot, you can create a violin plot to show the distribution of points for each group by setting kind = 'violin'.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'species', 
    hue  = 'sex',
    kind = 'violin',
    order = ['Adelie', 'Gentoo', 'Chinstrap']
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17017f19f00>

By default, we get completely separate "violins" for our categorical variables, but if we set split = True, we get the top and bottom half of each violin mapped to our hue variable.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data = penguins, 
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'species', 
    hue  = 'sex',
    kind = 'violin',
    split = True,
    order = ['Adelie', 'Gentoo', 'Chinstrap']
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1701a7d9180>

If we want to represent the data with a bar plot with error bars, we can set kind = 'bar'. By default the estimator is the mean but you can give another function to this. Here, I've chosen to represent 1 standard deviation with the error bars. It’s bad practice to show only summary statistics, and showing the raw points along with the mean bars is better but it isn't clear to me how to achieve this with seaborn.

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(
    data      = penguins, 
    x         = 'species', 
    y         = 'bill_length_mm', 
    hue       = 'sex',
    kind      = 'bar',
    estimator = 'mean',
    errorbar  = ('sd', 1),
    order     = ['Adelie', 'Gentoo', 'Chinstrap']
    )
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17031199300>

Facetting¶

When we have multiple variables we wish to represent in a plot, we can create clearer, more effective visualisations by splitting the data across subplots, or facets. In seaborn this is controlled with the col argument that, perhaps confusingly, doesn't control colour but controls which variable is mapped to different columns of plots.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species',
    col  = 'sex'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x170318c6a70>

We can control the number of rows and columns by setting the col_wrap argument to the number of columns of facets we wish to get.

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(
    data     = penguins,
    x        = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y        = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue      = 'species',
    col      = 'sex',
    col_wrap = 1
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17031b0de10>

We can map specific variables to the rows and columns of a grid by first defining a grid with FacetGrid(), defining which variables we want to be mapped to the rows and columns (and any other mappings like hue). Then, we use the map() method to set our x and y variable mappings.

In [ ]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(
    penguins, 
    row           = 'sex', 
    col           = 'island', 
    hue           = 'species', 
    margin_titles = True
)

g.map(sns.scatterplot, 'bill_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm')
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17031bdf490>

Customising labels¶

If we want to share our plot with others in a report or publication, we’ll probably want it to have a nice title and labels. We can add a title and axis labels by using the set() method. If we want to change or remove the legend title, we need to use the _legend.set() method.

In [ ]:
p2 = sns.relplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species'
)

p2.set(
    xlabel = 'Bill length (mm)',
    ylabel = 'Bill depth (mm)',
    title  = 'Penguin bill length and depth by species'
)

p2._legend.set(title = '')
Out[ ]:
[None]

Customising the look of your plot with styles¶

You can customise each feature of your plots as you like, but a good place to start is using one of seaborn's built-in styles using the set_style() function.

In [ ]:
sns.set_style('whitegrid')

sns.relplot(
    data = penguins,
    x    = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue  = 'species'
)
Out[ ]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x17032647460>
In [ ]:
sns.set_style('white')

sns.relplot(

    y    = 'bill_depth_mm',

sns.set_style('darkgrid')

Finishing touches and saving plots¶

We can control the colour palette by setting palette to one of seaborn's built-in colour palettes. We can use the despine() method to offset the axes if we wish, and the set() method to set labels and axis limits. We use the move_legend() function to place the legend where we want it, including frameon = True to draw its border.

Finally, we use savefig() (from the matplotlib.pyplot module) to write the image out as a file, setting bbox_inches = 'tight' to ensure no plot components get clipped. The function infers the image format from the file extension and can be one of eps, 'jpeg', 'jpg', 'pdf', 'pgf', 'png', 'ps', 'raw', 'rgba', 'svg', 'svgz', 'tif', 'tiff', or 'webp'.

In [ ]:
p3 = sns.relplot(
    data    = penguins,
    x       = 'bill_length_mm', 
    y       = 'bill_depth_mm',
    hue     = 'species',
    palette = 'Set2'
)

p3.despine(offset = 30, trim = False)

p3.set(
    xlabel = 'Bill length (mm)',
    ylabel = 'Bill depth (mm)',
    title  = 'Penguin bill length and depth by species',
    ylim   = (12, 22),
    xlim   = (30, 60)
)

p3._legend.set(title = '')

sns.move_legend(p3, 'lower left', bbox_to_anchor = (.1, .1), frameon = True)

plt.savefig('plots/penguin_plot.png', dpi = 300, bbox_inches = "tight")
